# Rust Engine Rules

## Module Organization

```
goud_engine/src/
├── core/       # Error types (thiserror), events, math (glam wrappers), generational handles
├── ecs/        # Entity-Component-System: World, Entity, Components, Systems, Queries
├── assets/     # AssetServer, loaders, hot-reload (notify), audio (rodio)
├── libs/       # Low-level subsystems: graphics (OpenGL), platform (GLFW)
├── ffi/        # FFI boundary — see ffi-sdk rule
├── sdk/        # Native Rust SDK — zero-overhead API mirroring FFI surface
└── lib.rs      # Public API surface, re-exports
```

## Error Handling

- Use `thiserror` for error types — define in `core/error.rs`
- Library functions return `Result<T, GoudError>`, never panic
- Map errors at module boundaries with `.map_err()` or `?`

## Generational Handles

- `Handle<T>` in `core/handle.rs` for safe resource references
- Entity IDs use generational index + generation pair (`Entity::new(index, generation)`)
- Never store entity IDs as raw `u32` — always use `Entity` type

## Component Patterns

- Components are plain data structs — derive `Debug`, `Clone`
- No side-effectful methods on components
- Storage via `SparseSet<T>` for O(1) access and cache-friendly iteration
- Transform hierarchy: `Transform2D` → `GlobalTransform2D` via propagation system

## System Patterns

- Systems implement the `System` trait or use function systems
- Query components from `World` — type-safe generic queries
- System scheduling via `Schedule` with `CoreStage` ordering
- Never access `World` internals directly; go through queries

## Resource Management

- Resources stored in `World` via `Resources` container
- Access with `Res<T>` (read) and `ResMut<T>` (write) system params
- Insert resources before systems that depend on them

## Crate Configuration

- Crate type: `cdylib` (for FFI shared library) + `rlib` (for Rust consumers)
- All public API goes through `lib.rs` re-exports
